title: Smylie Kaufman wins in his 5th PGA Tour start
text:
Smylie Kaufman wins in his 5th PGA Tour start Originally published October 25, 2015 at 7:43 pm Smylie Kaufman won the Shriners Hospitals for Children Open in his fifth PGA Tour start, closing with a 10-under-par 61 in Las Vegas. Six players tied for second, one stroke behind the 23-year-old. By Seattle Times staff The Associated Press 
LAS VEGAS – Smylie Kaufman won the Shriners Hospitals for Children Open on Sunday in his fifth PGA Tour start, shooting a 10-under-par 61 and waiting more than two hours while rival after rival fell just short. 
Kaufman played the final 11 holes in 9 under, with an eagle and seven birdies. The 23-year-old former Louisiana State golfer closed with a 20-foot birdie putt on the par-4 18th to finish at 16-under 268 at TPC Summerlin. 
Kaufman earned $1.152 million. 
Six players tied for second place at 15 under. Most Read Stories Unlimited Digital Access. $1 for 4 weeks. 
Kevin Na (67) was tied for the lead after 16 holes, but bogeyed the par-3 17th after flubbing a chip shot. 
Others who tied for second were Patton Kizzire (63), Cameron Tringale (66), Jason Bohn (66), Alex Cejka (66) and third-round leader Brett Stegmaier (69). 
Former Washington Husky Nick Taylor (72) tied for 25th place at 9 under. Kyle Stanley (69) of Gig Harbor and Ryan Moore (71) of Puyallup were among those tied for 43rd at 5 under. Kevin Chappell (72), who owns a home in Kirkland, tied for 62nd at 2 under. Ko rises to No. 1 
TAIPEI, Taiwan – Lydia Ko ran away with the LPGA Taiwan Championship to regain the No. 1 spot in the world ranking. 
The 18-year-old New Zealander shot a 7-under 65 and won by nine strokes with a 20-under 268 total. She earned $300,000 for her 10th LPGA Tour victory. Ko is the youngest player to win 10 events on any major tour. Other tournament 
• Justin Rose of England closed with a 2-under 68 to win the Hong Kong Open by a stroke over Lucas Bjerregaard (69) of Denmark. Rose had a 17-under total. Seattle Times staff
